# macOS Menu Bar App Rules

Use these rules when building or modifying macOS menu bar apps.

## App Structure

- Prefer native macOS APIs for menu bar behavior.
- Use `MenuBarExtra` for SwiftUI-first menu bar apps when it fits the product.
- Use `NSStatusItem`/AppKit when advanced control is needed.
- Keep menu bar state minimal, fast, and reliable.
- Do not block the main thread during menu opening, status refresh, or background polling.

## Menu Bar UX

- The menu bar item must communicate state clearly:
  - idle
  - active
  - syncing/processing
  - error
  - disabled/unavailable
- Avoid noisy animations or frequent status changes.
- Provide a clear primary action near the top of the menu/popover.
- Provide access to settings/preferences.
- Provide a quit command.
- Keep menu/popover content compact and scannable.

## Popovers and Windows

- Use a popover for quick interactions.
- Use a separate settings window for configuration-heavy screens.
- Do not overload the menu bar popover with full app complexity.
- Preserve window focus behavior expected on macOS.
- Avoid stealing focus unexpectedly.

## Background Work

- Use timers, async tasks, or background services carefully.
- Pause or throttle background work when not needed.
- Persist user settings.
- Restore app state safely after restart.
- Surface failures through visible status, not hidden logs only.

## Permissions and Privacy

- Request macOS permissions only when needed.
- Explain why permissions are needed before triggering system prompts.
- Never collect clipboard, screen, microphone, accessibility, contacts, or file data without explicit user action and visible product reason.
- Store secrets in Keychain where appropriate.
- Avoid writing sensitive data to logs.

## Launch and Login Behavior

- Do not add login items without explicit user approval.
- If login-at-startup is offered, make it user-toggleable.
- Verify launch behavior after packaging changes.

## Quality Gate

Before considering menu bar work complete:

- The app launches.
- The menu bar item appears.
- The primary menu/popover opens reliably.
- Settings/preferences are reachable if present.
- Quit works.
- Permission prompts are justified and not repeated unnecessarily.
- Background tasks do not freeze the menu.
